All I can say is that I TOTALLY AGREE with the previous reviewer. We must have been eating dinner together that night!! The comments are exactly my thoughts. Enough said!!

Rating: 2
The good news is the glaze. The combination of flavors is exceptional, with the sharpness of the lemon, the sweetness of the peach preserves, and the bite of the chile powder and hot sauce balancing each other very well indeed. These flavors combined in one of the best barbeque sauces I have ever tasted. Unfortunately, it was largely wasted on ribs that were rubbery, fatty, and uninspired after baking, a technique that appears to be unsuited to this cut. The next time I make this sauce, I will use it on ribs cooked on a slow fire in a closed kettle. If I had to do them in the oven, I would reduce the heat to 325 and cook them for about twice as long, turning occasionally, and only adding the sauce during the last 20 minutes to minimize the mess caused by burning sugar.